Working on the model structure definition from Python.

See #118

Adding a radiation computing function

Adding a function to compute potential clear-sky direct solar radiation as defined by Hock (1999).
The algorithms are adapted from Olson, M., & Rupper, S. (2019). Impacts of topographic shading on
direct solar radiation for valley glaciers in complex topography. Cryosphere, 13(1), 2940.
https://doi.org/10.5194/tc-13-29-2019 And the code: https://zenodo.org/record/1948620.
My Python translation has been tested against the original code until the incidence angle computation.
The computation of the true anomaly is using a different formula than those I found so far and might
need to be changed.

Implementing the netcdf, constants

Implementing the creation of the netcdfs by decomposing the input period as Julian days, computing the radiation and bringing back the correct Julian days into a netcdf file. Debugged the transformation of the aspect to radian in the angle of incidence computations. I removed the computation of the hour angle, and exported the between-steps (azimuth, zenith etc as netcdf). I also added the constants.py file that I forgot in the last commit.

Cleaned version

Version that computes the radiation without additional outputs, and print. The radiation obtained presents several very low, negative values, but these values are systematically identical. They are probably incorrectly set to zero. I used the mean height of the DEM to compute the radiation, but I could use the local pixel heights. The formula for the True anomaly is also to be investigated more in details.
